The increase in the Kingdom's investment will dry up the need to get aid by providing unlimited financing sources. Hassan Saleh, a market consultant told Gulf Times at the time: “The closing short-term positions and the return of funds led to an interest in the market in the past two months … If you add to the positive sentiment on the market due to low petroleum prices and the expected government reforms in the country, we are seeing buying interests, which are reflected in the market rise.”

A year has passed since then, but Qatar's foreign reserves are still at an all-time low thanks to the high USD spending the state was forced to direct as compensation owed to the World Cup 2022 contractors for breaching agreement signed with the winning bidder. Former Minister of Economy and Trade Sheikh Ahmed bin Jassim al-Thani revealed in an interview with Aljazeera that Saudi Arabia adopted a blackmailing tactic to slow down the pace of Qatar's investment in Uganda by forcing the country's President Museveni to retort negatively and carry out demonstrations that would make interaction with him politically costly.
